   "source": [
    "# Paired T-Test for Equivalence using TOST (Two One-Sided Tests)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",

   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},

     "execution_count": 5,

   ],
   "source": [
    "sample_size = df.shape[0]\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df['difference'] = df['bp_before'] - df['bp_after']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### It is necessary to confirm the distribution is approximately uniform and check for outliers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",

  {

   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

  },
  {

    "# check for normal distribution (difference)\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Setting Equivalence Bounds (confidence interval)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In equivalence test is necessary to establish a confidence interval (low/high bounds).\n",
    "\n",
    "I will use a 95% confidence interval (statistical_significance = 0.05)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "confidence_interval = .95\n",
    "statistical_significance = 0.05"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# code from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15033511/compute-a-confidence-interval-from-sample-data\n",
    "\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import scipy.stats\n",
    "\n",
    "def mean_confidence_interval(data, confidence):\n",
    "    a = 1.0 * np.array(data)\n",
    "    n = len(a)\n",
    "    m, se = np.mean(a), scipy.stats.sem(a)\n",
    "    h = se * scipy.stats.t.ppf((1 + confidence) / 2., n-1)\n",
    "    return m, m-h, m+h"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "mean 5.091666666666667\n",
      "mean- 2.0705568567756942\n",
      "mean+ 8.11277647655764\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "[m, mn, mp] = mean_confidence_interval(df['difference'], confidence_interval)\n",
    "print('mean', m)\n",
    "print('mean-', mn)\n",
    "print('mean+', mp)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Compute TOST (using statsmodels)\n",
    "\n",
    "http://www.statsmodels.org/0.9.0/generated/statsmodels.stats.weightstats.ttost_paired.html#statsmodels.stats.weightstats.ttost_paired\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "pvalue 0.02500000000176085\n",
      "t_1, p_value_1, degrees_of_freedom_1 1.9800998764260063 0.02500000000176085 119.0\n",
      "t_2, p_value_2, degrees_of_freedom_2 -1.9800998764260065 0.025000000001760832 119.0\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# http://www.statsmodels.org/0.9.0/generated/statsmodels.stats.weightstats.ttost_paired.html#statsmodels.stats.weightstats.ttost_paired\n",
    "# statsmodels.stats.weightstats.ttost_paired(x1, x2, low, upp, transform=None, weights=None)[source]\n",
    "\n",
    "from statsmodels.stats import weightstats\n",
    "\n",
    "# null hypothesis: md < low or md > upp alternative hypothesis: low < md < upp\n",
    "\n",
    "[pvalue, tuple1, tuple2] = weightstats.ttost_paired(x1=df['bp_before'], x2=df['bp_after'], low=mn, upp=mp)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Returns:\t\n",
    "#pvalue (float)  pvalue of the non-equivalence test\n",
    "#t1, pv1, df1 (tuple)  test statistic, pvalue and degrees of freedom for lower threshold test\n",
    "#t2, pv2, df2 (tuple)  test statistic, pvalue and degrees of freedom for upper threshold test\n",
    "\n",
    "[t_1, p_value_1, degrees_of_freedom_1] = tuple1\n",
    "[t_2, p_value_2, degrees_of_freedom_2] = tuple2\n",
    "\n",
    "print('pvalue', pvalue)\n",
    "print('t_1, p_value_1, degrees_of_freedom_1', t_1, p_value_1, degrees_of_freedom_1)\n",
    "print('t_2, p_value_2, degrees_of_freedom_2', t_2, p_value_2, degrees_of_freedom_2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "REJECT H0 ! - we are confident the distributions are equivalent !\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# (copied from wikipedia...) When both these one-sided tests can be statistically rejected, we can\n",
    "# conclude that L <  < U, or that the observed effect falls within the equivalence bounds and is\n",
    "# statistically smaller than any effect deemed worthwhile, and considered practically equivalent\n",
    "\n",
    "# If the calculated p-value is below the threshold chosen for statistical significance\n",
    "# (usually the 0.10, the 0.05, or 0.01 level), then the null hypothesis is rejected in favor\n",
    "# of the alternative hypothesis.\n",
    "\n",
    "if (p_value_1  < statistical_significance) and (p_value_2 < statistical_significance):\n",
    "    print('REJECT H0 ! - we are confident the distributions are equivalent !')\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print('CANNOT REJECT H0...')"
   ]
  },
